{:level 0, :title "Tactics", :path ["Tactics"], :contents [:div [:p "In this section, you'll learn how to accomplish your goals and make it safely back to base."]], "Munition Selection" {:level 1, :title "Munition Selection", :path ["Tactics" "Munition Selection"], :contents [:div [:p "As more and more munitions get added to the game, it can be difficult to keep track of which does what, and when to use which—even for veteran pilots. This section aims to offer guidance based on mission type."] [:p "TK"]]}, "Defensive" {:level 1, :title "Defensive", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive"], :contents nil, "Avoiding Missiles" {:level 2, :title "Avoiding Missiles", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive" "Avoiding Missiles"], :contents [:div [:p "We've all been there. You're cruising along, minding your own business, when suddenly the missile launch warning goes off. The key to surviving these encounters is to stay calm and analyze the situation."] [:p "When you get the \"missile launched\" notification, the things you need to pay attention to are:"] [:ol [:li "The orange \"MISSILE\" warning light"] [:li "\"Fox Two\" or \"Fox Three\" calls on the radio " "(" "if flying with wingmen" ")"]] [:table [:thead [:tr [:th {:alignment "center"} "\"MISSILE\" "] [:th {:alignment "center"} "\"Fox\" "] [:th {:alignment "left"} "Situation"]]] [:tbody [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:em "no"] " "] [:td {:alignment "center"} "\"Fox Two\" "] [:td {:alignment "left"} [:em "Probably"] ", an ally has launched an IR missile"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "Yes "] [:td {:alignment "center"} [:em "none"] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "You've been targetted by an active radar-guided missile"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:em "no"] " "] [:td {:alignment "center"} [:em "none"] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "You've been targetted by a heat-seeking missile"]]]] [:p "If a call such as \"Fox 2\" " "(" "infrared-guided" ")" " or \"Fox 3\" " "(" "active radar-guided" ")" " is accompanied by a missile launch notification, and you don't see the orange warning light, as indicated above this missile is " [:em "probably"] " an ally's aimed at somebody else, but you should still be wary. A red " [:code "M"] " on the RWR is also a good indication that you've been targetted by an active radar-guided missile."] [:p "Properly identifying the type of threat is crucial to survival, as some evasion techniques are mutually exclusive, as you will see."]], "General Strategies" {:level 3, :title "General Strategies", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive" "Avoiding Missiles" "General Strategies"], :contents [:div [:p "Situational awareness is crucial to survival. As soon as you get a \"missile launched\" notification, you have a potentially very short window of time before the missile locks onto you. In that window, it may be possible to confuse the missile's tracking systems by launching countermeasures, but it becomes much harder to do so once it has a lock " "(" "indicated by the orange \"MISSILE\" warning light" ")" "."] [:p "For radar-guided missiles, it may still be possible to confuse the missile " "(" "see " [:a {:href "#beaming"} "Beaming"] " below" ")" " but in general at this point your best bet is to avoid it. Here, the things to remember are that:"] [:ol [:li "The missile is trying to go where it thinks you " [:em "will be"] ", not where you  are."] [:li "The missile has a finite amount of fuel and energy that it can use to reach  you."]] [:p "With that in mind, here are some general strategies:"] [:ul [:li "Don't run away from the missile—it will have the advantage in a direct  chase. Instead, prefer flying perpendicular to it, if you can, or at  an angle towards it, so it has to waste its energy maneuvering."] [:li "Dive toward the ground, or a mountain, and fly low, to try to trick the  missile into crashing into the ground."] [:li "Alternatively, if you have enough speed, climb into the air to try to  make the missile waste its energy following you, keeping in mind your  angle with the missile."]]]}, "Active radar-guided missiles" {:level 3, :title "Active radar-guided missiles", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive" "Avoiding Missiles" "Active radar-guided missiles"], :contents [:div [:p "Flares will generally not help too much against these, and chaff is situational. The general strategies of forcing the incoming missile to expend all of its energy before it can reach you, as described above, are very relevant. Two common maneuvers for accomplishing this are covered below."]], "F-Pole Maneuver" {:level 4, :title "F-Pole Maneuver", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive" "Avoiding Missiles" "Active radar-guided missiles" "F-Pole Maneuver"], :contents [:div [:p "F-Pole refers to the distance between the launching aircraft and its target at the moment of missile impact. An F-Pole maneuver is a BVR strategy designed to maximize this distance, with the idea that by engaging bandits at a longer range you are more likely to stay out of their engagement zone and, consequently, more likely to survive the encounter."] [:p "The prototypical example of the F-Pole maneuver involves an enemy aircraft on a head-on trajectory towards your aircraft. In this situation, it is recommended to \"crank\" left or right of the aircraft so that your flight path is about a level 40-50 degrees away from theirs " "(" "you probably want to turn in the direction of the shorter angle, to conserve energy. As they continue to approach, even if they adjust course to try to intercept, any radar-guided missile they launch will have to make a hard turn to try to intercept you."] [:p "If they do launch a missile, you can then abuse its guidance systems by turning in towards the enemy aircraft, probably about a 90-100 degree turn in the opposite direction of your original turn. At this point, you will be in a good position to launch a missile of your own, as you will have closed more distance and, by keeping the enemy within 50 degrees of you, you should still have a radar lock on them. This sharp turn will force the incoming missile to waste even more energy on a second turn, hopefully making it easy for you to avoid " "(" "if it's fully active, or if it's semi-active but your missile doesn't take out the enemy aircraft before the missile gets close enough to intercept you" ")" "."] [:p "For further reference on the F-Pole, see " [:a {:href "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c-Lx4SFMWdU"} "this Youtube video"] "."]]}, "Beaming" {:level 4, :title "Beaming", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive" "Avoiding Missiles" "Active radar-guided missiles" "Beaming"], :contents [:div [:p "The way doppler radar tracking works, if you are moving toward or away from the radar site it will very easily be able to detect you against the open sky. When beaming, you maintain a perpendicular flight path to the line of site from the radar site, so that you are neither moving towards nor away from it, making it harder for the missile to distinguish you from the landscape."] [:p "If the missile is launched at you from above " "(" "IE another aircraft" ")" " then beaming the missile may be sufficient to make it unable to distinguish you from the terrain. If it was launched from below you, however, such as from a surface-mounted missile launcher, you will need to make use of chaff."] [:p "While maintaining a perpendicular flight path to the radar site, particularly as the missile approaches your aircraft, begin launching a slow but steady stream of chaff. Hopefully this will confuse the missile and it will break off. If it does not, you may need to switch strategies."] [:p "It is important to remember that once you have established a perpendicular flight path, you will need to bank slightly towards the radar site so that you are orbiting it, in order to maintain the perpendicular path; otherwise, you will start to flight away from the radar site, and you will no longer be beaming."]]}}, "Heat-seeking missiles" {:level 3, :title "Heat-seeking missiles", :path ["Tactics" "Defensive" "Avoiding Missiles" "Heat-seeking missiles"], :contents [:div [:p "Infrared/Heat-seeking missiles like the " [:a {:href "#aim-9-sidewinder"} "AIM-9"] " are sometimes simpler to avoid than active radar-guided. Using the techniques above cannot hurt, of course—dogfighting tends to be about correct energy management—however the fact that IR missiles can be confused by appropriate use of Flares tends to make them somewhat easier to evade."] [:p "It is important to remember, however, that " [:em "flares are not magic"] ". They can draw away IR-seeking missiles by providing a hotter-looking target for the seeker head, but if your engines are still in full afterburner then they won't be enough to distract the missile. If you are hoping to use Flares to evade an IR-seeking missile, you " [:em "must"] " lower your throttle to put out a smaller IR signature than your flares" "!"]]}}}}